# Granting Local Administrator Privileges Using Group Policy

## Overview

This lab demonstrates how to delegate local administrator rights to a specific Active Directory security group using Group Policy Preferences instead of manually adding users to the local Administrators group on each workstation.

This approach follows enterprise best practices by assigning permissions to security groups rather than individual users.

---

## Objective

Grant local administrator privileges to members of the **IT SUPPORT ADMINS** security group on all computers inside the **Workstation PCs OU**.

---

## Lab Environment

- Windows Server 2022 Domain Controller
- Windows 11 Client
- VMware Workstation
- Active Directory Domain Services
- Group Policy Management
- Domain: CHARLYCYBER.LOCAL

---

## Steps Performed

### 1. Created an Active Directory Security Group

Created:

- IT SUPPORT ADMINS

Added:

- ITguyuser1

---

### 2. Created a New Group Policy

Created:

IT SUPPORT ADMIN RIGHTS

Linked it to:

Workstation PCs OU

---

### 3. Configured Group Policy Preferences

Navigated to:

Computer Configuration

→ Preferences

→ Control Panel Settings

→ Local Users and Groups

Configured:

- Action: Update
- Group: Administrators (built-in)
- Added:
    CHARLYCYBER\IT SUPPORT ADMINS

---

### 4. Applied the Policy

Executed:

gpupdate /force

Successfully updated:

- Computer Policy
- User Policy

---

### 5. Verification

Verified that:

CHARLYCYBER\IT SUPPORT ADMINS

appeared inside:

Local Administrators Group

using:

net localgroup administrators

---

### 6. Functional Testing

Logged in as:

ITguyuser1

Successfully performed administrative actions including:

- Managing Windows Services
- Starting/Stopping Print Spooler
- Opening Computer Management

without requiring administrator credentials.

